SIMPLE: seal
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Seal
<hw>Seal</hw> <pr>(s⟦emac⟧l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>sele</ets>, AS. <ets>seolh</ets>; akin to OHG. <ets>selah</ets>,
Dan. <ets>sael</ets>, Sw. <ets>sj⟦aum⟧l</ets>, Icel.
<ets>selr</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any aquatic carnivorous
mammal of the families <fam>Phocidae</fam> and
<fam>Otariidae</fam>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Seals inhabit seacoasts, and are found principally in
the higher latitudes of both hemispheres. There are numerous species,
bearing such popular names as <stype>sea lion</stype>, <stype>sea
leopard</stype>, <stype>sea bear</stype>, or <stype>ursine seal</stype>,
<stype>fur seal</stype>, and <stype>sea elephant</stype>. The bearded
seal (<spn>Erignathus barbatus</spn>), the hooded seal (<spn>Cystophora
cristata</spn>), and the ringed seal (<spn>Phoca foetida</spn>), are
northern species. See also <cref>Eared seal</cref>, <cref>Harp
seal</cref>, <cref>Monk seal</cref>, and <cref>Fur seal</cref>, under
<er>Eared</er>, <er>Harp</er>, <er>Monk</er>, and <er>Fur</er>. Seals
are much hunted for their skins and fur, and also for their oil, which
in some species is very abundant.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Harbor seal</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the common
seal (<spn>Phoca vitulina</spn>). It inhabits both the North Atlantic
and the North Pacific Ocean, and often ascends rivers; -- called also
<altname>marbled seal</altname>, <altname>native seal</altname>,
<altname>river seal</altname>, <altname>bay seal</altname>,
<altname>land seal</altname>, <altname>sea calf</altname>, <altname>sea
cat</altname>, <altname>sea dog</altname>, <altname>dotard</altname>,
<altname>ranger</altname>, <altname>selchie</altname>,
<altname>tangfish</altname>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Seal</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Seal
<hw>Seal</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>seel</ets>, OF.
<ets>seel</ets>, F. <ets>sceau</ets>, fr. L. <ets>sigillum</ets> a
little figure or image, a seal, dim. of <ets>signum</ets> a mark, sign,
figure, or image. See <er>Sign</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, and cf.
<er>Sigil</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An engraved or inscribed stamp,
used for marking an impression in wax or other soft substance, to be
attached to a document, or otherwise used by way of authentication or
security.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Wax, wafer, or other tenacious substance, set to an
instrument, and impressed or stamped with a seal; <as>as, to give a deed
under hand and <ex>seal</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Till thou canst rail the <qex>seal</qex> from off my bond⟦br⟧
Thou but offend'st thy lungs to speak so loud.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which seals or fastens; esp., the wax or wafer
placed on a letter or other closed paper, etc., to fasten it.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>That which confirms, ratifies, or makes stable; that
which authenticates; that which secures; assurance.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Under
the <xex>seal</xex> of silence.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Like a red <qex>seal</qex> is the setting sun⟦br⟧
On the good and the evil men have done.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>An arrangement for preventing the entrance or return
of gas or air into a pipe, by which the open end of the pipe dips
beneath the surface of water or other liquid, or a deep bend or sag in
the pipe is filled with the liquid; a draintrap.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Great seal</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Great</er>.</cd>
-- <col><b>Privy seal</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Privy</er>,
<pos>a.</pos></cd> -- <col><b>Seal lock</b></col>, <cd>a lock in which
the keyhole is covered by a seal in such a way that the lock can not be
opened without rupturing the seal.</cd> -- <col><b>Seal
manual</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Manual</er>, <pos>a.</pos></cd> --
<col><b>Seal ring</b></col>, <cd>a ring having a seal engraved on it, or
ornamented with a device resembling a seal; a signet ring.</cd>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Seal</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Seal
<hw>Seal</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Sealed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sealing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>selen</ets>; cf. OF.
<ets>seeler</ets>, <ets>seieler</ets>, F. <ets>sceller</ets>, LL.
<ets>sigillare</ets>. See <er>Seal</er> a stamp.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To set or affix a seal to; hence, to authenticate; to confirm; to
ratify; to establish; <as>as, to <ex>seal</ex> a deed</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And with my hand I <qex>seal</qex> my true heart's love.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To mark with a stamp, as an evidence of standard
exactness, legal size, or merchantable quality; <as>as, to <ex>seal</ex>
weights and measures; to <ex>seal</ex> silverware</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To fasten with a seal; to attach together with a
wafer, wax, or other substance causing adhesion; <as>as, to
<ex>seal</ex> a letter</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Hence, to shut close; to keep close; to make fast;
to keep secure or secret.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Seal</qex> up your lips, and give no words but
⟦ldquo⟧mum⟦rdquo⟧.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To fix, as a piece of iron in a wall, with cement,
plaster, or the like.</def> <rj><au>Gwilt.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To close by means of a seal; <as>as, to
<ex>seal</ex> a drainpipe with water</as>. See 2d <er>Seal</er>,
5.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Among the Mormons, to confirm or set apart as a
second or additional wife.</def> <mark>[Utah, U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If a man once married desires a second helpmate . . . she is
<qex>sealed</qex> to him under the solemn sanction of the church.</q>
<rj><qau>H. Stansbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Seal</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Seal
<hw>Seal</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To affix one's seal, or a
seal.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will <qex>seal</qex> unto this bond.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sea laces</ent>⟦br⟧
